{"id": "47075", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=47075", "title": "Gebdu, Mountain Breaker", "text": " is a &lt;a href=\"demon\"&gt;demon&lt;/a&gt;, and a member of the &lt;a href=\"Hearthrot\"&gt;Hearthrot&lt;/a&gt;.\nBiography.\nA creature of solitude, Gebdu strives to purge the land of life, leaving behind a bare and desolate world. Gebdu relies on his massive strength and size to collapse caverns, shatter towns and &lt;a href=\"human\"&gt;people&lt;/a&gt; to the paste on which &lt;a href=\"Spall%20of%20Gebdu\"&gt;his children&lt;/a&gt; feed. Of his own accord, Gebdu would grind the same region to dust for eons. But the &lt;a href=\"Lord%20of%20Destruction\"&gt;Lord of Destruction&lt;/a&gt; granted him a vision of &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary\"&gt;Sanctuary&lt;/a&gt;, and he now wishes to see it all crumble at once.\nGebdu's corruption created sandstorms in &lt;a href=\"Shassar%20Sea\"&gt;Shassar Sea&lt;/a&gt;.\nAfter his &lt;a href=\"death\"&gt;death&lt;/a&gt;, Gebdu's &lt;a href=\"Gebdu%27s%20Glare\"&gt;head&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Stone%20Heart\"&gt;heart&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Clenching%20Carnelian\"&gt;fists&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Obelisk%20Sole\"&gt;foot&lt;/a&gt; were sealed within the &lt;a href=\"Helliquary\"&gt;Helliquary&lt;/a&gt;.\nIn-game.\nGebdu is the third Hearthrot &lt;a href=\"Helliquary\"&gt;Helliquary&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"boss\"&gt;boss&lt;/a&gt; to be defeated. He becomes available at II. \nCombat.\nGebdu is fought in the &lt;a href=\"Hall%20of%20the%20Mountain%20Breaker\"&gt;Hall of the Mountain Breaker&lt;/a&gt;.\nSecond Phase (Spalls).\nAt around overall health ( health bars), Gebdu leaps to the center of the arena and fissures into &lt;a href=\"Spall%20of%20Gebdu\"&gt;Spalls&lt;/a&gt;. Each Spall is immune to knockback, and usually mirror each other in their attacks. When killed, they shatter into piles of rocks.\nThird Phase.\nWhen the last Spall is at health, it retreats to the center of the arena where it combines with the remains of its brethren to reform Gebdu. Gebdu retains all abilities from phase one, sans the totems. In addition,he uses\nFourth Phase (Spalls).\nAt of his overall health, Gebdu retreats to the center of the arena and fissures into Spalls. These Spalls are slightly weaker than the first batch and retain all their skills, albeit slightly weaker.\nFifth Phase (Sandstorm).\nWhen the last Spall is at health, it retreats to the center of the arena where it combines with the remains of its brethren to reform Gebdu. Gebdu creates a sandstorm at the edge of the arena, forcing the player to remain near the center. He retains all abilities from the previous phases, but prioritizes his prolonged AoE attacks (cave ins, golems and totems)."}
{"id": "2468", "revid": "43924158", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2468", "title": "Geglash", "text": "Geglash can be found in &lt;a href=\"The%20Secret%20of%20the%20Vizjerei\"&gt;Act II&lt;/a&gt; of \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\" and is a warrior who spends a lot of time drinking in &lt;a href=\"Atma\"&gt;Atma&lt;/a&gt;'s public house and seems to think of nothing but drinking and fighting, though some dialogue with the player character suggests he may be interested in pursuing a romantic relationship with Atma, and that he possesses a measure of sympathy for her situation. He admires the s for their ferocity, and for their dual wielding abilities. He tells characters that he never developed the latter ability, but can carry a &lt;a href=\"swords\"&gt;sword&lt;/a&gt; and a wineskin simultaneously. He is afraid of one thing however, water, and he will not go near it or ships for any reason. He spends his days drunk in &lt;a href=\"Atma%27s%20Tavern\"&gt;Atma's Tavern&lt;/a&gt;, not much use as a soldier. He started drinking because the &lt;a href=\"demon\"&gt;demon&lt;/a&gt;s were getting too much for him.\nGeglash is one of two NPCs in the \"Diablo series\" who spends all of his time drinking; the other being &lt;a href=\"Farnham\"&gt;Farnham&lt;/a&gt; the Drunk from the original \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20%28Game%29\"&gt;Diablo&lt;/a&gt;\".\nDialogue.\nGossip about Geglash.\nSome of the other locals give their thoughts concerning Geglash."}
{"id": "22721", "revid": "3423357", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=22721", "title": "Gehennas", "text": "The Gehennas are &lt;a href=\"Craftable%20items\"&gt;crafted&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Legendary%20Items\"&gt;legendary&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"pants\"&gt;pants&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\". They require character level 60 to be worn. The level 70 crafted equivalent are &lt;a href=\"Skelon%27s%20Deceit\"&gt;Skelon's Deceit&lt;/a&gt;.\nCrafting.\nThe Gehennas can be crafted using the Plan: Gehennas, 42000 &lt;a href=\"gold\"&gt;gold&lt;/a&gt;, 15 &lt;a href=\"Reusable%20Parts\"&gt;Reusable Parts&lt;/a&gt;, 15 &lt;a href=\"Arcane%20Dust\"&gt;Arcane Dust&lt;/a&gt; and 20 &lt;a href=\"Veiled%20Crystal\"&gt;Veiled Crystal&lt;/a&gt;s."}
{"id": "50748", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50748", "title": "Geherit", "text": "Geherit was one of the elders of the &lt;a href=\"Inari\"&gt;Inari&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Ancients%27%20Cradle\"&gt;Ancients' Cradle&lt;/a&gt; during the onset of the affliction.\nBiography.\nAfter &lt;a href=\"Morwith\"&gt;Morwith&lt;/a&gt; and her followers absconded with the &lt;a href=\"Pathstone\"&gt;Pathstone&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Ymuthrus\"&gt;Ymuthrus&lt;/a&gt; became the island's new &lt;a href=\"Prevailing%20Wind\"&gt;Prevailing Wind&lt;/a&gt;. He ordered that any &lt;a href=\"Lilin\"&gt;Lilin&lt;/a&gt; who had ever advocated leaving the island was to be executed. Geherit and her fellow Inari were shocked, but only &lt;a href=\"Zatham\"&gt;Zatham&lt;/a&gt; spoke out against him. In retaliaton, Ymuthrus ordered Zatham to be submitted to the rite of &lt;a href=\"Purity%27s%20Penance\"&gt;Purity's Penance&lt;/a&gt;. It did not kill Zatham, but burned the eyes from his face. Ymuthrus then permitted him exile. Geherit noted that it was, by Ymuthrus's standards, generous.\nLater, Zatham returned to the Cradle in the company of &lt;a href=\"the%20Shard-seeker\"&gt;the Shard-seeker&lt;/a&gt;. Zatham attacked Ymuthrus, but was blasted away. Geherit advocated mercy, and asked Ymuthrus to entrust Zatham and the newcomer to her, so she could evaluate their claims. Ymuthrus agreed, but told her that whatever harm they brought would be inflicted on her tenfold. Geherit agreed to his terms, and asked Zatham and the Shard-seeker to follow her. She asked Zatham why he couldn't have held his grieviances inside, to which Zatham bitterly responded that this was how rot spread; unwillingness to speak its name.\nOutside &lt;a href=\"Exiles%27%20Repose\"&gt;Exiles' Repose&lt;/a&gt;, Geherit and Zatham discussed the situation. She pointed out that only Ymuthrus had taken Zatham's sight, not his fellow elders. Zatham responded that Ymuthrus was the worst of them, and emblematic of the rot that had taken the Inari. Geherit told him to save his anger for the &lt;a href=\"Cult%20of%20Terror\"&gt;Cult of Terror&lt;/a&gt;, and led them into &lt;a href=\"the%20Veiled%20Spring\"&gt;the Veiled Spring&lt;/a&gt;. Zatham told her that they had the Pathstone, which meant they could use it to reinforce the &lt;a href=\"Husk%20of%20Creation\"&gt;Husk of Creation&lt;/a&gt;. With that, Ymuthrus would see their worth. However, the time the Pathstone had spent away from the Cradle had unblanaced it. To use it, they had to restore its equilibrium. The Pathstone was given to the Shard-seeker, and she ordered them to take it to &lt;a href=\"Shieldholm\"&gt;Shieldholm&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe Shard-seeker returned after charging the Pathstone with the Father's Legacy. Geherit was overjoyed, and commented that with the Mother's Legacy, the Ancients' Cradle could be reforged. Zatham joined them after a short while. After they caught up on each other's progress, Geherit offered to peer into the spring for a vision of the cult's activities. The spring revealed a vision of the &lt;a href=\"Bride%20of%20Hell\"&gt;Bride of Hell&lt;/a&gt; with the shard at the &lt;a href=\"Husk%20of%20Creation\"&gt;Husk of Creation&lt;/a&gt;. After she told her companions of her vision, the Shard-seeker left for Lilith's shrine with renewed haste, while Zatham promised to do his best to delay the cult.\nZatham returned to the Veiled Spring with cultists. Together, they defeated Geherit and destroyed the spring. However, Zatham spared her, and left her trapped beneath rubble. The Shard-seeker later returned with &lt;a href=\"Tarzoine\"&gt;Tarzoine&lt;/a&gt;.\nIn-game.\nGeherit is an &lt;a href=\"NPC\"&gt;NPC&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\"."}
{"id": "49253", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49253", "title": "Gelatinous Remains", "text": " are &lt;a href=\"monster\"&gt;monster&lt;/a&gt;s formed from the &lt;a href=\"corpse\"&gt;corpse&lt;/a&gt;s of &lt;a href=\"human\"&gt;people&lt;/a&gt; that died in cursed swamps.\nLore.\nThe sump stench and spoiled water of the &lt;a href=\"Bilefen\"&gt;Bilefen&lt;/a&gt; earn the most alarm from sailors who skip over &lt;a href=\"Port%20Justinian\"&gt;Port Justinian&lt;/a&gt;. But the true curse of &lt;a href=\"Infested%20Quagmire\"&gt;the swamp&lt;/a&gt; is how little respect it has for the dead. Oozing mounds of mud and melted flesh gather mass as they scoot across the landscape, growing larger with each ship that arrives on their island. They also feed on &lt;a href=\"scavenger\"&gt;scavenger&lt;/a&gt;s.\nIn-game.\n are monsters in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\". They are found in the &lt;a href=\"Infested%20Quagmire\"&gt;Infested Quagmire&lt;/a&gt; of Bilefen."}
{"id": "30633", "revid": "164821", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=30633", "title": "Gelatinous Sire", "text": "The Gelatinous Sire, Nefarious Promulgator is a type of &lt;a href=\"Treasure%20Goblin\"&gt;Treasure Goblin&lt;/a&gt;, added in patch 2.2.0 of \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\".\nIt has the ability to split into two smaller Goblins on death, which all gain a brief moment of being immune to damage when they spawn. These smaller goblins, upon death, each split into three more again (to a total of six). The smallest six goblins drop \"double\" the loot of a full Goblin pack, therefore killing all six will grant twelve times the usual reward. Each has a separate escape timer, and they tend to run in different directions, therefore catching all six may be challenging. Only the smallest goblins drop any loot, and in the moment of splitting, have a brief moment of invulnerability.\nTo distinguish them from other types, Gelatinous Sire has bubble-like transparent blue appearance and an apparently deep voice.\nIn 4-player multiplayer games, the Sire will spawn 3 smaller goblins, each splitting into 3 more, to a total of 9 smallest goblins."}
